    <title>Combined summary - BIP30 and BIP34 interaction (was Re: [BIP Proposal] Buried Deployments)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T20:39:22.687249+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2016-November/013290.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Various discussions have taken place on the bitcoin-dev mailing list regarding the possibility of hash collisions in Bitcoin transactions and their potential impact on the security of the network. While some argue that hash collisions are unlikely to occur, others believe that they remain a possibility and could lead to serious problems if not addressed. The importance of preventing collisions in coinbase transactions is highlighted, with the committed height introduced to ensure their validity. BIP30 is no longer checked since it can only be violated by a hash collision.There are also determinism bugs related to hash collision issues that were introduced as supposed optimizations, which do not constitute consensus rules and should be considered non-consensus bugs. One issue raised in the discussion is the reliance of Bitcoin Core on the impossibility of hash collisions for maintaining consensus. While this is implemented in multiple places in the code, any implementation that invalidates blocks based on order of arrival is broken, as validity must be verifiable independently by all nodes.Eric Voskuil expresses concern over the possibility of a tx hash collision, which could produce a chain split if not handled properly. However, Peter Todd responded by stating that such an event would be highly unlikely since SHA256 is currently a secure algorithm with infeasible brute-force attacks against 256-bit keys. The discussion also touched on the issue of banning an invalid block hash, which is not purely a peer-to-peer protocol issue as some implementations ban it while others do not.The post recommends responsible development behavior to prevent and fix such bugs without requiring forks or BIPs. Another topic discussed was the possibility of duplicated txids due to hash collisions. While BIP34 aims to enforce block and transaction uniqueness, it does not explicitly reject collisions by consensus. The suggestion is made to draft a new BIP to address this issue, but it is noted that doing so would make it impossible to guard against chain splits due to pruning.Eric Voskuil explains why banning duplicate transaction hashes outright is not feasible as it would require spent transaction hashes to be retained forever, which goes against the concept of pruning nodes. Implementing such a ban would result in a chain split and a hard fork. It is noted that while BIP34 disallows exact duplicate transactions, different transactions can still have the same hash if their parents are identical.The post also recommends people contemplate the difference between unlikely and impossible, highlighting that the chance of random collision is very small but not zero. Betting Bitcoin and potentially the world's money on the unknowable is poor reasoning, especially given that the cost of not doing so is low. In addition, the discussion touches on the permanent blocking of a block in a peer-to-peer protocol design.Finally, the BIP30 regression hard fork is seen as a case of non-determinism, which produces undesired consequences such as destruction of all unspent outputs in the "replaced" transaction. The proposed fork is deemed as a premature optimization, and there are more significant opportunities to better organize code and improve performance. Bitcoin provides the mechanism to reject cheaply-produced invalid blocks quickly through headers first, avoiding arbitrary nodes that create non-determinism in exchange for speed. Any situation in which a node cannot provide deterministic validation of unordered blocks constitutes a non-consensus error, and fixing/preventing these bugs is responsible development behavior.</summary>
